		{"id":"7b5ec557e5b773a7","type":"text","text":"# Speaker notes — all slides\n\n**Total talk:** ~14–16 minutes + Q&A  \n**Tip:** Speak to the audience, not the slide. Glance at bullets; use these notes as your script.\n\n---\n\n## Slide 1 — Title (~45 sec)\n\nHello everyone, and thank you for being here.\n\nMy name is **Chris Dang**, and this is my final project for the **2026 Inference AI Course**: **Household Financial Intelligence**.\n\nThe tagline is **make your finance controllable and predictable**. The idea is simple: one place for your ledger, live bank data, documents, and AI answers — not scattered spreadsheets and guessing chatbots.\n\nThe live app is at **household-financial-web.vercel.app**. Today I’ll cover the problem, the solution, the tech stack, and what I learned building it.\n\n**Transition:** Let me start with why this matters.\n\n---\n\n## Slide 2 — Why it matters (~2 min)\n\nHousehold money is hard to manage for four reasons.\n\n**First — our money is everywhere.** Pay stubs, bank apps, PDF bills, spreadsheets — they don’t talk to each other. There’s no **single place** to see income, expenses, and obligations.\n\n**Second — simple questions are hard.** For example: Can we afford a **$20K trip to China in July**? How much have we put into **RESP, TFSA, or RRSP**? Do we have enough cash for the **second property tax installment in June**?\n\n**Third — documents don’t become usable data.** Insurance, car lease, tax notices sit in email and folders. You still dig them out manually.\n\n**Fourth — we need answers on the go.** Households shouldn’t open five banking apps to see disposable cash. They need **one view** — from the **web or Telegram** — without adding everything up by hand.\n\nGeneric AI chatbots are **unsafe for money** because they **hallucinate numbers**.\n\nMy answer: a **canonical ledger**, **deterministic forecasting**, **human-reviewed document ingestion**, and **AI limited to explanation** — on the **web** and **Telegram**.\n\n**Target users:** households — especially couples managing shared finances.\n\n**Transition:** Here’s how the app solves that in four pillars.\n\n---\n\n## Slide 3 — Solution (~2 min)\n\nThe solution has **four pillars**.\n\n**One — centralize in PostgreSQL.** Manual entries become ledger events. Upload PDFs → extract obligations → you confirm → they become events. Forecast and Q&A read the **same data** — no duplicate spreadsheets.\n\n**Two — live balances with Plaid.** Link bank accounts, sync checking into `current_cash`, keep balance history. Ledger plus Plaid gives a **six-month forecast** and **disposable assets**. **Engines compute; AI explains.**\n\n**Three — documents: RAG plus Obsidian.** Upload once: **RAG** so AI can answer from bill and contract text; **Obsidian** for a human-readable wiki. Files live in blob storage; confirmed amounts still land in the ledger.\n\n**Four — Telegram on the go.** In production, Telegram → n8n → Vercel API → reply. For local dev, **ngrok** and **Docker n8n**. Same secured API as the website — ledger, Plaid, forecast.\n\n\n**Transition:** Here’s the end-to-end flow on one slide.\n\n---\n\n## Slide 4 — How it works (~1.5 min)\n\nThree paths feed one system.\n\n**Documents:** upload PDF → extract → preview obligations → you confirm → ledger event → also indexed for RAG and Obsidian.\n\n**Live money:** Plaid Link → sync balances → checking feeds forecast opening cash → all accounts feed history and the disposable view on `/balances`.\n\n**Ask questions:** Scenario Chat or Telegram → the app **routes** the question — ledger lookup, what-if forecast, document RAG, or LangGraph multi-agent → answer with **numbers plus a short explanation**.\n\nThe rule on this slide: **AI explains and retrieves — it never invents totals** when the database and engines can compute them.\n\nI built in **Cursor**, deploy via **GitHub** to **Vercel**.\n\n**Transition:** I’ll walk through the tech stack — starting with how I built and ship the code.\n\n---\n\n## Slide 5 — Dev tools (~45 sec)\n\nThese are the **engineering tools** behind the project.\n\n**Jira Kanban** for backlog and tasks. **ESLint** for code quality. **GitHub Actions** for **CI/CD** — on every push we run tests, lint, and build. **Vercel Blob** stores uploaded PDFs in production.\n\nThis isn’t the user-facing app — it’s how I kept the project **merge-ready** and caught regressions early.\n\n**Transition:** The user-facing layer is the frontend.\n\n---\n\n## Slide 6 — Frontend (~1.5 min)\n\nThe **frontend** is what users see and click.\n\nI write **TypeScript** everywhere. **`.tsx` files** are UI — TypeScript plus **JSX**, HTML-like markup inside the code. Plain **`.ts`** is logic only — no screen.\n\n**React** breaks the UI into **components** with **state** — e.g. “Connect bank” disabled while loading.\n\n**Tailwind** styles with utility classes. **shadcn/ui** gives consistent Button, Card, and Input components.\n\n**Next.js** provides **pages** — `/ledger`, `/simulation`, `/balances` — plus **API routes** and **server rendering** for faster first load.\n\n**Node** runs the dev server locally, CI on GitHub, and the live app on **Vercel**.\n\nThe **browser** shows the UI and handles interactive pieces — Plaid Link, microphone, chat forms. Secrets stay on the server.\n\n**Transition:** When the user clicks or asks something, the backend takes over.\n\n---\n\n## Slide 7 — Backend (~1.5 min)\n\nThe **backend** is server-side logic and data.\n\n**Next.js API routes** receive requests — save ledger events, scenario chat, Plaid sync. The browser and Telegram only call **`/api/...`**; they never see database passwords.\n\n**Prisma** is the translator between TypeScript and SQL — typed queries to Postgres.\n\n**Postgres** is the **single source of truth** — events, documents, RAG chunks, Plaid history.\n\nLocally I use **Docker Postgres**; in production **Neon** in the cloud. Same schema, different connection URL.\n\n**Vercel** hosts the Next.js app. **DBeaver** is for me as developer — inspect tables and ER diagrams — not for end users.\n\n**Transition:** A second way into the same backend is automation.\n\n---\n\n## Slide 8 — Automation (~1 min)\n\n\n**Automation** is Telegram on your phone.\n\nUser sends a message in **Telegram**. **ngrok** provides a **public HTTPS URL** so Telegram can reach my local **n8n** on port **5678** in Docker. Remember: **Docker hosts n8n; ngrok delivers the webhook** — they’re not the same thing.\n\n**n8n** runs workflows with an AI agent and HTTP tools — add expense, ask forecast, read Plaid balance.\n\nEvery tool calls the **same Vercel API** as the website — ledger, Plaid, forecast — so phone and web never disagree.\n\n**Transition:** Inside that API, two AI pipelines handle documents and voice.\n\n---\n\n## Slide 9 — AI pipeline (~1.5 min)\n\n**Pipeline one — documents and RAG.**\n\nUpload PDF → extract text → **chunk** about a thousand characters with overlap → **embed** at 384 dimensions → store in **Postgres with pgvector**.\n\nWhen you ask a question, we embed the question, find the **top similar chunks**, and the LLM answers **only from those excerpts** — retrieve first, then generate.\n\n**Pipeline two — voice.**\n\nMic → audio → **`/api/stt/transcribe`** → **OpenAI Whisper** → text → same **scenario chat** as typing.\n\nImportant: AI **retrieves and explains**. Code in **`projection.ts`** and the ledger **compute** forecasts and totals.\n\n**Transition:** For the hardest questions, I added multi-agent routing.\n\n---\n\n## Slide 10 — Multi-agent / LangGraph (~1.5 min)\n\nSimple questions stay in **fast deterministic code** — like month totals.\n\nComplex ones — **“Can we afford $500/month for a car?”** — need several views. That’s **multi-agent** on **LangGraph**, hosted on **Railway** as a Python service.\n\n**Router** classifies intent and picks specialists:\n\n- **Cost** — cash flow and forecast snapshot  \n- **Payments** — bills and timing from the ledger  \n- **Investment** — Plaid accounts and balance trends  \n\n**Composer** merges their reports. Optional **writer** narrates in plain English **without changing the numbers**.\n\nFlow: user on **Vercel** → POST **`/orchestrate`** → **Railway LangGraph** → read-only calls back to Vercel APIs → answer with the **LangGraph multi-agent** route badge.\n\n**Transition:** Live bank data comes from Plaid.\n\n---\n\n## Slide 11 — Plaid (~1 min)\n\n**Plaid** is the live bank layer.\n\nUser connects through **Plaid Link** in the browser. My **Next.js API** exchanges tokens and syncs balances via the **Plaid REST API** — secrets only on the server. Data lands in **Neon** and powers **`/balances`**, the **investment specialist**, and **n8n tools**.\n\nWhy Plaid?\n\n- Live balances from linked accounts  \n- A complete **disposable-assets** picture  \n- AI answers grounded in **actual liquid cash**  \n- **Balance history** over time  \n\n**Transition:** To trust AI in finance, I also invested in evaluation.\n\n---\n\n## Slide 12 — Evals (~1 min)\n\nThree layers of testing.\n\n**One — Vitest unit tests** — 26-plus tests in CI: routing, parsers, forecast math, Plaid logic. Same input, same output — no live LLM.\n\n**Two — n8n evaluations** — a CSV dataset runs through the Telegram agent; we score reply similarity and review tool routing — ledger write vs Plaid vs forecast.\n\n**Three — manual smoke tests** — real Telegram write → appears on Ledger; Plaid sync on `/balances`; LangGraph badge on a complex question.\n\nVitest catches **wrong numbers**. n8n evals catch **wrong tool choice**. Manual tests catch **integration gaps** — env vars, deploy, end-to-end demo.\n\n**Transition:** Building this taught me a lot — challenges and learning.\n\n---\n\n## Slide 13 — Challenges & Learning (~1 min)\n\n**Challenges:**\n\n1. Understanding the full stack — frontend to backend, local to cloud.  \n2. Keeping Telegram working in **n8n Cloud** and **local Docker**.  \n3. **Hybrid AI routing** — when to use deterministic code, LangGraph, or a plain LLM.\n\n**Learning:**\n\n1. How to run and deploy a production app in the cloud.  \n2. How to wire **Vercel, Neon, Railway, Plaid, and n8n** together.  \n3. How to evaluate AI with **Vitest, n8n evals, and manual demos**.\n\n**Transition:** So what’s the impact, and what would I do differently?\n\n---\n\n## Slide 14 — Impact & Reflect (~1 min)\n\n**Impact:**\n\n1. **One place** for household money — ledger, bank, documents, forecast.  \n2. **Trustworthy AI** — route badges show deterministic code and Plaid, not guesses.  \n3. **Access anywhere** — web, voice, Telegram.  \n4. **Repeatable quality** — CI and evals.\n\n**Reflect:**\n\n1. **AI is a layer**, not the whole product — data and routing matter most.  \n2. **Start simple**, integrate one service at a time — local, then cloud, Plaid, LangGraph, n8n.  \n3. **Ship, test, iterate** — evals matter as much as features.  \n4. **Communicate clearly with AI** — explain intent, ask it to retell the plan, correct early.  \n5. **Treat AI like a teammate** — same idea: summarize back before it writes the wrong code.\n\n**Transition:** I’ll wrap up and take questions.\n\n---\n\n## Slide 15 — Thank you / Q&A (~30 sec)\n\nTo summarize: **Household Financial Intelligence** brings ledger, live Plaid data, documents, hybrid AI routing, and Telegram into one system — with **deterministic math first** and **AI second**.\n\nThank you for your time and attention. I’m happy to take **questions**, or show a quick **live demo** on the website — `/ledger`, `/balances`, `/simulation` — or Telegram if n8n is running.\n\n*(Use `Presentation/PRESENTATION_QA.md` for rehearsed answers.)*\n\n---\n\n## Timing cheat sheet\n\n| Slides | Topic | ~Time |\n|--------|--------|-------|\n| 1 | Title | 0:45 |\n| 2 | Problem | 2:00 |\n| 3 | Solution | 2:00 |\n| 4 | How it works | 1:30 |\n| 5–7 | Dev / FE / BE | 3:30 |\n| 8–11 | Automation / AI / LangGraph / Plaid | 5:00 |\n| 12–14 | Evals / Challenges / Impact | 3:00 |\n| 15 | Close | 0:30 |\n\n---\n\nIf you want this saved into `Presentation/SLIDES.md` or `PRESENTATION_SPEAKER.md` in the repo, switch to Agent mode and ask me to add the file.","x":-660,"y":-3820,"width":1260,"height":2360}
